05009nam a22007095i 9781442675216DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162003onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013964481  a97814426752167 a10.3138/97814426752162doi  a(DE-B1597)464495  a(OCoLC)946712468  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHD7096.C2 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a368.4/4/09711 aPorter, Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGendered States :bWomen, Unemployment Insurance, and the Political Economy of the Welfare State in Canada, 1945-1997 /cAnn Porter. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Comparative Political Economy and Public Policy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Gender and the Political Economy of the Welfare State: Theoretical Considerations -- tPART I: Contradictions and Transformations in Families, Markets, and the Welfare State, 1940-1971 -- t2. Gender and the Construction of the Postwar Welfare State -- t3. From Exclusion to Entitlement: Pregnancy, Maternity, and the Canadian State -- t4. Women into the Labour Force, UI Review, and Expansion -- tPART II: On the Path to Neoliberalism: Gender, Crisis, and Restructuring -- t5. Social Reproduction in a Transition Period: Maternity, Rights, and Conceptions of Equality -- t6. Gender, Economic Crisis, and Welfare State Restructuring in the 1970s -- t7. The Conservatives in Power: A Polarized Debate and the Shift to a Market-Based Approach -- t8. Consolidating Neoliberal Reforms: Globalization, Multi-Earner Families, and the Erosion of State Support for the Unemployed -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the period since the Second World War there has been both a massive influx of women into the Canadian job market and substantive changes to the welfare state as early expansion gave way, by the 1970s, to a prolonged period of retrenchment and restructuring. Through a detailed historical account of the Unemployment Insurance (UI) program from 1945 to 1997, Ann Porter demonstrates how gender was central both to the construction of the post-war welfare state, as well as to its subsequent crisis and restructuring. Drawing on a wide range of sources (including archival material, UI administrative tribunal decisions, and documents from the government, labour and women's groups) she examines the implications of restructuring for women's equality, as well as how women's groups, labour and the state interacted in efforts to shape the policy agenda.Porter argues that, while the post-war welfare state model was based on a family with a single male breadwinner, the new model is one that assumes multiple family earners and encourages employability for both men and women. The result has been greater formal equality for women, but at the same time the restructuring and reduction of benefits have undermined these gains and made women's lives increasingly difficult. Using concepts from political economy, feminism, and public policy, this study will be of interest across a range of disciplines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aUnemployment insurancezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxEmploymentzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267521640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442675216423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442675216.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4 